{
  "esm": "0.4.0",
  "metadata": {
    "name": "Solids",
    "description": "Aggregate container for the 19 solid-phase salt species in the ISORROPIA II inorganic thermodynamic equilibrium model. Composes 19 named Solid instances — one per solid salt that can form in the K+-Ca2+-Mg2+-NH4+-Na+-SO42--NO3--Cl--H2O system — into a single subsystem bundle. Each Solid carries a single state variable M(t) [mol/m^3] representing the molarity of that salt in air; in isolation M is conserved (D(M)/dt = 0). Source/sink terms are injected through the coupling mechanism when Solids is composed into the parent Isorropia system. Reference: Fountoukis and Nenes (2007), ISORROPIA II.",
    "tags": [
      "aerosol",
      "isorropia",
      "solid-phase",
      "thermodynamics",
      "inorganic-aerosol",
      "composed-model"
    ],
    "created": "2026-05-21T00:00:00Z",
    "authors": [
      "Aerosol.jl contributors",
      "EarthSciModels migration (esm-6w1)"
    ],
    "references": [
      {
        "citation": "Fountoukis, C. and Nenes, A. (2007). ISORROPIA II: a computationally efficient thermodynamic equilibrium model for K+-Ca2+-Mg2+-NH4+-Na+-SO42--NO3--Cl--H2O aerosols. Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 7(17), 4639-4659. https://doi.org/10.5194/acp-7-4639-2007"
      }
    ]
  },
  "models": {
    "Solids": {
      "reference": {
        "citation": "Fountoukis, C. and Nenes, A. (2007) ISORROPIA II, Atmos. Chem. Phys. 7(17), 4639-4659 — solid-phase salt species. Migrated from Aerosol.jl src/isorropia/solid.jl:22 `Solids` (esm-6w1).",
        "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/isorropia/solid.jl:22\n\nUpstream `Solids` at the reference commit has two layers. The active code declares 7 ionic state variables — NH4(t), Na(t), Ca(t), K(t), Mg(t), Cl(t), NO3(t) — each with unit u\"mol/m^3\" and guess=1e-14, and returns System(eqs=[], t; name) with no equations. Immediately above those declarations, 19 named Solid instance assignments are commented out (lines 23-41): CaNO32, CaCl2, CaSO4, KHSO4, K2SO4, KNO3, KCl, MgSO4, MgNO32, MgCl2, NaCl, NaNO3, Na2SO4, NaHSO4, NH4Cl, NH4NO3, NH42SO4, NH4HSO4, NH43HSO42. The commented-out block represents the original salt-tracking design; the active code switched to tracking ionic totals in the solid phase.\n\nESM design rationale: The migration tracker entry for Solids specifies features=[variables, coupling.couple] and depends_on=Solid. This description fits the original 19-subsystem design (each Solid instance is a Solid component composed via coupling), not the ionic-total design of the active code. Because (1) the tracker explicitly records the dependency on Solid and (2) the 19-subsystem design is more faithful to the ISORROPIA II literature (which tracks individual solid-salt phases), this ESM implements the original commented-out design. The 19 Solid instances are encoded as inline subsystems (ESS spec 4.7), each with one state variable M and one conserved equation D(M)/dt = 0.\n\nThe 19 solid salts correspond to the full K+-Ca2+-Mg2+-NH4+-Na+-SO42--NO3--Cl--H2O case from ISORROPIA II:\n  NH42SO4 — (NH4)2SO4, ammonium sulfate\n  NH4HSO4 — NH4HSO4, ammonium bisulfate\n  LC      — (NH4)3H(SO4)2, letovicite (standard ISORROPIA abbreviation)\n  NH4NO3  — NH4NO3, ammonium nitrate\n  NH4Cl   — NH4Cl, ammonium chloride\n  Na2SO4  — Na2SO4, sodium sulfate\n  NaHSO4  — NaHSO4, sodium bisulfate\n  NaNO3   — NaNO3, sodium nitrate\n  NaCl    — NaCl, sodium chloride\n  CaSO4   — CaSO4, calcium sulfate\n  CaNO32  — Ca(NO3)2, calcium nitrate\n  CaCl2   — CaCl2, calcium chloride\n  K2SO4   — K2SO4, potassium sulfate\n  KHSO4   — KHSO4, potassium bisulfate\n  KNO3    — KNO3, potassium nitrate\n  KCl     — KCl, potassium chloride\n  MgSO4   — MgSO4, magnesium sulfate\n  MgNO32  — Mg(NO3)2, magnesium nitrate\n  MgCl2   — MgCl2, magnesium chloride\n\nEach subsystem M(t) [mol/m^3] satisfies D(M)/dt = 0 in isolation (the conserved-tracer convention, matching the standalone Solid component and elemental_carbon.esm). The upstream Solid carries guess=1e-20 mol/m^3; this is preserved as the default initial condition for each M in this composite model.\n\nIn the full Isorropia system, the parent component supplies source/sink equations for each M through coupling; the D(M)/dt = 0 equations exist here solely to make the standalone model self-contained and its tests mechanically runnable.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): each subsystem integrates D(M)/dt = 0, the same trivial ODE as the standalone Solid. Solver round-off is ~1e-15 relative; rel=1e-9 leaves six orders of margin, matching solid.esm."
      },
      "tolerance": {
        "rel": 1e-09
      },
      "variables": {},
      "equations": [],
      "subsystems": {
        "NH42SO4": {
          "variables": {
            "M": {
              "type": "state",
              "units": "mol/m^3",
              "default": 1e-20,
              "description": "Molarity of (NH4)2SO4 (ammonium sulfate) solid in air. Conserved: D(M)/dt = 0 in standalone use; coupled Isorropia adds source/sink terms."
            }
          },
          "equations": [
            {
              "lhs": {"op": "D", "args": ["M"], "wrt": "t"},
              "rhs": 0
